Step 1: Identify quick assets. These are assets that can be quickly turned into cash. In this balance sheet, they include:
• Cash on Hand
• Bank Deposits
• Interest Receivable
• Accounts Receivable

Step 2: Compute the sum of quick assets (using End_amounts):
• Cash on Hand = 1,254,762.92
• Bank Deposits = 1,982,606.98
• Interest Receivable = 7,775.44
• Accounts Receivable = 335,967.05
Sum of quick assets = 1,254,762.92 + 1,982,606.98 + 7,775.44 + 335,967.05 = 3,581,112.39

Step 3: Identify Current Liabilities (from End_amounts):
• Accounts Payable = 3,333,720.00
• Taxes Payable = 42,584.04
Total Current Liabilities = 3,333,720.00 + 42,584.04 = 3,376,304.04

Step 4: Calculate Quick Ratio:
Quick Ratio = (Quick Assets) / (Current Liabilities)
Quick Ratio = 3,581,112.39 / 3,376,304.04 ≈ 1.06

Thus, the Quick Ratio as of the end of the reporting period is approximately 1.06.
